Hello Kyle,

Thank you for checking for me. I'm working on getting this escalated to development.

Please navigate to the SEEK Scan job's properties and make sure the log level is set to DEBUG. It defaults to WARNING, and I can't remember if we changed it to DEBUG already.

The exact structure of your Job tree is likely different, but you need to right-click on the SEEK System Scan job and click Properties.
[cid:image001.png@01DB3101.3E25E200]



Is the Log Level already set to DEBUG?

[cid:image002.png@01DB3101.3E25E200]


If not, please set it to DEBUG, save, then run the job again.
Once the job fails, export the Job (include all job components) and attach the .zip to the ticket:

[cid:image003.png@01DB3101.3E25E200]

If the Log Level was already set to DEBUG, you skip straight to exporting the job.

Thank you,

Joshua Sexton

Hello Kyle,

Thank you for that data. Is your application server a virtual machine? We've seen this behavior before where the application throws out of memory errors even though the server shows low RAM utilization. It turned out that the Hypervisor was running out of RAM.

If it is a virtual machine, please check the available RAM on the hypervisor.

Thank you,

Hello Kyle,

I'm sorry to see the page file didn't help. There is something else to look at. Could you please run a PowerShell command for me, then attach the output?

Run PowerShell as an administrator and navigate to Netwrix Enterprise Auditor's install directory. Default directory: "C:Program Files (x86)STEALTHbitsStealthAUDIT"

Run the command:
Get-ChildItem -Recurse -Filter "system.data.sqlite.dll" | Format-List -property *version* > SQLiteVersion.txt

It should create a file in Netwrix Enterprise Auditor's install directory called SQLiteVersion.txt
It will look something like this:

[cid:image004.png@01DB3101.3E25E200]

Please attach that file to the ticket. I want to see which FileVersions are listed.

Thank you,

Hello Kyle,

I'm sorry; I misspoke. You are correct that the SQL server is not likely in play here.

Regarding the page file, I double checked with a senior engineer, and we recommend having the page file configured so that it only uses one drive. The issue seems to be that Windows does a poor job splitting the page file across multiple drives.
Disable "Automatically manage paging file for all drive"
Set whichever drive is the largest or typically has the most free-space to "System managed size"
Set the other drive to "No paging file"
Reboot the server for the change to take effect

[cid:image005.png@01DB3101.3E25E200]

The new error, "...illegal operation attempted on a registry key that has been marked for deletion" typically just means you need to reboot the server. If you make the page file change, you need to reboot anyway.

I know each of these scan attempts takes days to finish/fail. I'm sorry for the hassle, but please let me know if this helps.

Thank you,

Joshua Sexton

Hello Kyle,

I'm sorry; I misspoke. You are correct that the SQL server is not likely in play here.

Regarding the page file, I double checked with a senior engineer, and we recommend having the page file configured so that it only uses one drive. The issue seems to be that Windows does a poor job splitting the page file across multiple drives.
Disable "Automatically manage paging file for all drive"
Set whichever drive is the largest or typically has the most free-space to "System managed size"
Set the other drive to "No paging file"
Reboot the server for the change to take effect

[cid:image005.png@01DB31C4.1DCFA4A0]

The new error, "...illegal operation attempted on a registry key that has been marked for deletion" typically just means you need to reboot the server. If you make the page file change, you need to reboot anyway.

I know each of these scan attempts takes days to finish/fail. I'm sorry for the hassle, but please let me know if this helps.

Thank you,

Hello Kyle,

I'm sorry; I misspoke. You are correct that the SQL server is not likely in play here.

Regarding the page file, I double checked with a senior engineer, and we recommend having the page file configured so that it only uses one drive. The issue seems to be that Windows does a poor job splitting the page file across multiple drives.
Disable "Automatically manage paging file for all drive"
Set whichever drive is the largest or typically has the most free-space to "System managed size"
Set the other drive to "No paging file"
Reboot the server for the change to take effect

[cid:image005.png@01DB3411.0515BA40]

The new error, "...illegal operation attempted on a registry key that has been marked for deletion" typically just means you need to reboot the server. If you make the page file change, you need to reboot anyway.

I know each of these scan attempts takes days to finish/fail. I'm sorry for the hassle, but please let me know if this helps.

Thank you,

Hello Kyle,

I'm sorry; I misspoke. You are correct that the SQL server is not likely in play here.

Regarding the page file, I double checked with a senior engineer, and we recommend having the page file configured so that it only uses one drive. The issue seems to be that Windows does a poor job splitting the page file across multiple drives.
Disable "Automatically manage paging file for all drive"
Set whichever drive is the largest or typically has the most free-space to "System managed size"
Set the other drive to "No paging file"
Reboot the server for the change to take effect

[cid:image013.png@01DB3BFC.1155BAB0]

The new error, "...illegal operation attempted on a registry key that has been marked for deletion" typically just means you need to reboot the server. If you make the page file change, you need to reboot anyway.

I know each of these scan attempts takes days to finish/fail. I'm sorry for the hassle, but please let me know if this helps.

Thank you,

Hello Kyle,

I'm sorry; I misspoke. You are correct that the SQL server is not likely in play here.

Regarding the page file, I double checked with a senior engineer, and we recommend having the page file configured so that it only uses one drive. The issue seems to be that Windows does a poor job splitting the page file across multiple drives.
Disable "Automatically manage paging file for all drive"
Set whichever drive is the largest or typically has the most free-space to "System managed size"
Set the other drive to "No paging file"
Reboot the server for the change to take effect

[cid:image006.png@01DB3BFD.FC852330]

The new error, "...illegal operation attempted on a registry key that has been marked for deletion" typically just means you need to reboot the server. If you make the page file change, you need to reboot anyway.

I know each of these scan attempts takes days to finish/fail. I'm sorry for the hassle, but please let me know if this helps.

Thank you,

Hello Kyle,

I'm sorry; I misspoke. You are correct that the SQL server is not likely in play here.

Regarding the page file, I double checked with a senior engineer, and we recommend having the page file configured so that it only uses one drive. The issue seems to be that Windows does a poor job splitting the page file across multiple drives.
Disable "Automatically manage paging file for all drive"
Set whichever drive is the largest or typically has the most free-space to "System managed size"
Set the other drive to "No paging file"
Reboot the server for the change to take effect

[cid:image006.png@01DB3C00.7575C2C0]

The new error, "...illegal operation attempted on a registry key that has been marked for deletion" typically just means you need to reboot the server. If you make the page file change, you need to reboot anyway.

I know each of these scan attempts takes days to finish/fail. I'm sorry for the hassle, but please let me know if this helps.

Thank you,

Joshua Sexton

Hello Kyle,

I'm sorry; I misspoke. You are correct that the SQL server is not likely in play here.

Regarding the page file, I double checked with a senior engineer, and we recommend having the page file configured so that it only uses one drive. The issue seems to be that Windows does a poor job splitting the page file across multiple drives.
Disable "Automatically manage paging file for all drive"
Set whichever drive is the largest or typically has the most free-space to "System managed size"
Set the other drive to "No paging file"
Reboot the server for the change to take effect

[cid:image006.png@01DB3C01.4AC88250]

The new error, "...illegal operation attempted on a registry key that has been marked for deletion" typically just means you need to reboot the server. If you make the page file change, you need to reboot anyway.

I know each of these scan attempts takes days to finish/fail. I'm sorry for the hassle, but please let me know if this helps.

Thank you,
